{{Shrine | Name = {{ill|Sakai Ōji|ja|境王子|qq=draft|qq=draft}} | image = [[File:境王子跡.jpg|250px|thumb|Site of {{ill|Sakai Ōji|ja|境王子|qq=draft|qq=draft}}]] | location = {{ill|Sakai-ku|ja|堺区|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Sakai, Osaka|ja|堺市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Osaka Prefecture|ja|大阪府|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, Japan | coordinates = | deity = | Affiliation = {{ill|Kumano Kōdō|ja|熊野古道|1=Kumano Kodō|qq=draft|qq=draft}} - {{ill|Kumano Pilgrimage|ja|熊野信仰|1=Kumano Three Shrines|lt=Kumano faith|qq=draft|qq=draft}} | Established = | Map = }}
'''{{ill|Sakai Ōji|ja|境王子|qq=draft|qq=draft}}''' (境王子) was the 7th of the {{ill|Kumano Ōji|ja|九十九王子|1=Kujūku Ōji|2=ja|3=九十九王子|4=fr|5=Kujūkuōji|1=Kujūku Ōji|1=Kujūku Ōji|1=Kujūku Ōji|qq=draft|qq=draft}} shrines, part of the historical {{ill|Kumano Kōdō|ja|熊野古道|1=Kumano Kodō|qq=draft|qq=draft}} pilgrimage routes.
== location == The shrine is believed to have been located near the current {{ill|Kitadaidei-chō|ja|北田出井町|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in {{ill|Sakai-ku|ja|堺区|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Sakai, Osaka|ja|堺市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. The name "Sakai" (meaning "border") is derived from the area's historical position at the boundary of the ancient provinces of {{ill|Settsu Province|ja|摂津国|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Kawachi Province|ja|河内国|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, and {{ill|Izumi Province|ja|和泉国|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.
References to Sakai Ōji appear in historical documents, such as the 1081 ({{ill|Eihō|ja|永保|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 1) record 'Fujiwara no Tamefusa Kyōki' (藤原為房卿記), where it is referred to as "Wakasaikai no Shōdō" (和泉堺之小堂), marking the first appearance of the name "Sakai" in historical texts.
The shrine was later relocated to the {{ill|Kumano Shrine (Sakai)|ja|熊野神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in Yuyachō, Sakai (now along {{ill|Ōdōri-suji|ja|大道筋|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in {{ill|Kumanochō Higashi 1-chōme|ja|熊野町東1丁|qq=draft|qq=draft}}). In 1908 ({{ill|Meiji era|ja|明治|1=Meiji era|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 41), this Kumano Shrine was merged with {{ill|Sugawara Shrine (Sakai)|ja|菅原神社 (堺市)|lt=Sugawara Shrine|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (located at 2-1-38 Ebisunochō Higashi, Sakai-ku), leaving the original site of Sakai Ōji uncertain.
However, historical documents indicate that the {{ill|Kumano Kōdō|ja|熊野街道|1=Kumano Kaidō|qq=draft|qq=draft}} passed through the eastern part of Sakai, intersecting with the {{ill|Nagao Kaidō|ja|長尾街道|qq=draft|qq=draft}} near {{ill|Hōtate Shrine|ja|方違神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, and passed west of Emperor {{ill|Hanzei|ja|反正天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft}}'s tomb. Based on these clues, Sakai Ōji is believed to have been located just north of Hōtate Shrine. The {{ill|Bunkyū 3 Revised Sakai Great Map|ja|文久三年改正堺大絵図|qq=draft|qq=draft}} even includes references to "Oguri-michi" (小栗道) and "Ōji-ga-ue" (王子ヶ飢), hinting at the shrine’s historical presence.
Today, a stone monument marking the "Site of Sakai Ōji" stands in {{ill|Ōji-ga-ue Park|ja|王子ヶ飢公園|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (3-4-6 Kitadaidei-chō, Sakai-ku), donated from {{ill|Kumano Hongū Taisha|ja|熊野本宮大社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in {{ill|Hongū, Tanabe, Wakayama|ja|本宮町|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, now part of {{ill|Tanabe, Wakayama|ja|田辺市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.
== Gallery == <gallery> File:境王子跡.jpg|Site of {{ill|Sakai Ōji|ja|境王子|qq=draft|qq=draft}} </gallery>
== Access == * '''Ōji-ga-ue Park:''' About 850m northeast from {{ill|Sakaihigashi Station|ja|堺東駅|qq=draft|qq=draft}} on the {{ill|Nankai Kōya Line|ja|南海高野線|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, operated by {{ill|Nankai Electric Railway|ja|南海電気鉄道|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. ** From Sakaihigashi Station, head north along the railway towards Namba, and turn east after the third railway crossing. * '''{{ill|Sugawara Shrine (Sakai)|ja|菅原神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}}:''' About 300m southeast from {{ill|Hanataguchi Station|ja|花田口停留場|qq=draft|qq=draft}} on the {{ill|Hankai Line|ja|阪堺電気軌道阪堺線|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, operated by {{ill|Hankai Tramway|ja|阪堺電気軌道|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.
