{{Shrine | Name = {{ill|Sakai Ōji|ja|境王子|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sakai Ōji|qq=}} | image = [[File:境王子跡.jpg|250px|thumb|Site of {{ill|Sakai Ōji|ja|境王子|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sakai Ōji|qq=}}]] | location = [[:en:Sakai-ku, Sakai|Sakai-ku]], [[:en:Sakai|Sakai, Osaka]], [[:en:Osaka Prefecture|Osaka Prefecture]], Japan | coordinates = | deity = | Affiliation = [[:en:Kumano Kodō|Kumano Kodō]] - {{ill|Kumano Pilgrimage|ja|熊野信仰|1=Kumano shrine|lt=Kumano Three Shrines|lt=Kumano faith|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumano Pilgrimage|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumano Three Shrines|qq=}} | Established = | Map = }}
'''{{ill|Sakai Ōji|ja|境王子|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sakai Ōji|qq=}}''' (境王子) was the 7th of the {{ill|Kumano Ōji|ja|九十九王子|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|1=Kujūku Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|2=ja|3=九十九王子|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|4=fr|5=Kujūkuōji|1=Kujūku Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|1=Kujūku Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|1=Kujūku Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumano Ōji|13=User:Immanuelle/Kujūku Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|qq=}} shrines, part of the historical [[:en:Kumano Kodō|Kumano Kodō]] pilgrimage routes.
== location == The shrine is believed to have been located near the current {{ill|Kitadaidei-chō|ja|北田出井町|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kitadaidei-chō|qq=}} in [[:en:Sakai-ku, Sakai|Sakai-ku]], [[:en:Sakai|Sakai, Osaka]]. The name "Sakai" (meaning "border") is derived from the area's historical position at the boundary of the ancient provinces of [[:en:Settsu Province|Settsu Province]], [[:en:Kawachi Province|Kawachi Province]], and [[:en:Izumi Province|Izumi Province]].
References to Sakai Ōji appear in historical documents, such as the 1081 ([[:en:Eihō|Eihō]] 1) record 'Fujiwara no Tamefusa Kyōki' (藤原為房卿記), where it is referred to as "Wakasaikai no Shōdō" (和泉堺之小堂), marking the first appearance of the name "Sakai" in historical texts.
The shrine was later relocated to the [[:en:Kumano shrine|Kumano Shrine (Sakai)]] in Yuyachō, Sakai (now along {{ill|Ōdōri-suji|ja|大道筋|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōdōri-suji|qq=}} in {{ill|Kumanochō Higashi 1-chōme|ja|熊野町東1丁|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumanochō Higashi 1-chōme|qq=}}). In 1908 ([[:en:Meiji era|Meiji era]] 41), this Kumano Shrine was merged with {{ill|Sugawara Shrine (Sakai)|ja|菅原神社 (堺市)|lt=Sugawara Shrine|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sugawara Shrine (Sakai)|qq=}} (located at 2-1-38 Ebisunochō Higashi, Sakai-ku), leaving the original site of Sakai Ōji uncertain.
However, historical documents indicate that the {{ill|Kumano Kōdō|ja|熊野街道|1=Kumano Kaidō|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumano Kōdō|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumano Kaidō|qq=}} passed through the eastern part of Sakai, intersecting with the {{ill|Nagao Kaidō|ja|長尾街道|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nagao Kaidō|qq=}} near {{ill|Hōtate Shrine|ja|方違神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hōtate Shrine|qq=}}, and passed west of Emperor [[:en:Emperor Hanzei|Hanzei]]'s tomb. Based on these clues, Sakai Ōji is believed to have been located just north of Hōtate Shrine. The {{ill|Bunkyū 3 Revised Sakai Great Map|ja|文久三年改正堺大絵図|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Bunkyū 3 Revised Sakai Great Map|qq=}} even includes references to "Oguri-michi" (小栗道) and "Ōji-ga-ue" (王子ヶ飢), hinting at the shrine’s historical presence.
Today, a stone monument marking the "Site of Sakai Ōji" stands in {{ill|Ōji-ga-ue Park|ja|王子ヶ飢公園|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōji-ga-ue Park|qq=}} (3-4-6 Kitadaidei-chō, Sakai-ku), donated from [[:en:Kumano Hongū Taisha|Kumano Hongū Taisha]] in {{ill|Hongū, Tanabe, Wakayama|ja|本宮町|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hongū, Tanabe, Wakayama|qq=}}, now part of [[:en:Tanabe, Wakayama|Tanabe, Wakayama]].
